ACM CHI conference, which could be his prior work. However, the exact title of the 1988 paper is not clear. The next step should focus on verifying if Khan's 1988 paper is the one referenced and retrieve its title.\n</reflection>\n\n<plan>\nTo find the first paper authored by Khan, I will search for \"Imran Naeem Khan ACM CHI 1988 paper\" using the google_search tool. This will help confirm if the 1988 paper is his first and retrieve its title. If successful, this will answer the user's query. If not, I will search for Murano's prior publications next.\n</plan>\n\n<action>\ntool: google_search\nparameters: {\"query\": \"Imran Naeem Khan ACM CHI 1988 paper\", \"num_results\": 5}\n</action>']\n[Observation 4: 'Tool 'wikipedia_knowledge_searcher' executed.\nResult: {\n  \"output\": \"Search results for 'Linear Menus ACM CHI 88':\\n1. Don Hopkins\\n2. 3D human–computer interaction\\n3. Multi-touch\\n4. Touchscreen\\n\\nExtracted text:\\nDon Hopkins is an artist and programmer specializing in human computer interaction and computer graphics. He is an alumnus of the University of Maryland and a former member of the University of Maryland Human–Computer Interaction Lab.\\nHe inspired Richard Stallman, who described him as a \\\"very imaginative fellow\\\", to use the term copyleft. He coined Deep Crack as the name of the EFF DES cracker. He ported the SimCity computer game to several versions of Unix and developed a multi player version of SimCity for X11, did much of the core programming of The Sims, and developed robot control and personality simulation software for Will Wright's Stupid Fun Club.\\nHe developed and refined pie menus for many platforms and applications including window managers, Emacs, SimCity and The Sims, and published a frequently cited paper about pie menus at CHI'88 with John Raymond Callahan, Ben Shneiderman and Mark Weiser. He has published many free software and open source implementations of pie menus for X10, X11, NeWS, Tcl/tk, ScriptX, ActiveX,